occurrenceRemarks: Phylum: Arthropoda Class: Pycnogonida Order: Pantopoda Morphology: These sea spiders have four pairs of legs and are bilaterally symmetric. They have chelicera and a proboscis on their anterior end, and a femur and coxae on their posterior end. They have an oviger attached to their first body segment, which is used for carrying eggs. Fun Fact: The legs of sea spiders are thought to contain some of their essential organs, due to their lack of a body. Using their legs, they are able to move fluids through their body. Their gonads are also located in the legs. As they grow, their legs get more porous, which aids in oxygen uptake. Research has suggested that this could improve their outcomes in response to warming oceans.
